Found the bug. Look at `isRetryable` (line 681-696):

```javascript
isRetryable(err) {
  if (err.code === 'ETIMEDOUT' || err.code === 'ECONNREFUSED' || ...) return true;
  if (err.message && (err.message.includes('timeout') || err.message.includes('ETIMEDOUT'))) return true;
  const status = err.status || err.statusCode || (err.response && err.response.status);
  if (status && RETRYABLE_STATUS.has(status)) return true;


```

The function checks for OpenAI and Anthropic SDK errors, but when `selfhosted_stt` fails with an exit code error, none of these conditions match—there's no network error code, the message doesn't contain timeout keywords, and there's no HTTP status to check—so it implicitly returns undefined and the error isn't retried.

This means if OpenAI Whisper fails with a retryable status, the chain continues to `selfhosted_stt`, but when that fails with exit code 127, the chain stops immediately instead of falling through to Groq Whisper or Deepgram. The bug is that self-hosted STT failures aren't recognized as retryable, breaking the entire fallback chain.

```

javascript
async _selfHostedSTT(audioBuffer, filename, contentType, options) {
  if (!selfHostedAudio || !this.selfHostedSTTAvailable) {
    throw new Error('Self-hosted STT not available');
  }
  const result = await selfHostedAudio.transcribe(audioBuffer, filename, contentType);
  return result;
}
```

The self-hosted STT checks that the binary and model files exist (which they do, based on the logs), then spawns the whisper process, but when it fails with exit code 127 due to a missing library, `isRetryable()` returns undefined and the chain halts.

I need to verify whether OpenAI Whisper is also failing, since if it works the chain would never reach self-hosted STT. The logs show zero transcription attempts in 24 hours, which could mean either nobody tried voice features or the error happens before logging. The simpler fix is to make self-hosted STT errors retryable so the fallback chain continues to Groq and Deepgram. The chain fails because self-hosted's exit code 127 isn't treated as retryable, so it stops before trying Groq and Deepgram. I need to either make self-hosted errors retryable, fix its initialization to properly detect unavailability on Render, or remove the binary entirely. I should also verify whether the OpenAI proxy itself has issues handling audio transcription. The core issue is that if OpenAI fails, the self-hosted fallback breaks the entire chain instead of continuing to Groq and Deepgram. I need to either make the self-hosted error handling retryable, actually verify the binary works during initialization, or add a catch-all for self-hosted errors in the retry logic—the most thorough approach is fixing the initialization to genuinely test whether the binary can run. I need to check whether the whisper-cli binary is actually committed to the repo or if it's generated during setup, since that determines whether I can simply remove it or need to handle it differently.

